<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5> one could do with something • one couldn’t do with something</xh5><p> <i>one could do with something—</i>1. one could make use of or benefit from smth.: You look as if you <u>could do with</u> a wash and brush up. <i>Cf.: one could do without something</i>—one could dispense with smth.; one could manage in spite of not having smth.: There were times when physicists ran from philosophers, being sure they <u>could do without</u> their advice and recommendations. 2. is used as an indirect way of asking for smth.: I <u>could just do with</u> a nice cup of tea and a smoke.</p><p><i>one couldn’t do with something—</i>one couldn’t put up with or tolerate smth.: I just <u>couldn’t do with</u> only one pair of pants because I would have to do laundry too many times.</p> </entry>
